As is well known, Eu 3+ among some special compound hosts, such as borates [ 19], phosphates [ 20], and aluminates [ 21], can also be reduced to Eu 2+ in air at a high temperature. It is suggested that all these compounds contain rigid tetrahedral BO 4, PO 4, AlO 4, or octahedral AlO 6 group framework, surrounding and insulating the produced Eu 2+ ions from oxygen [ 21, 22]. Zeolites, as one kind of aluminosilicate, not only are natural minerals, but also can be synthesized in industry at a lower cost [ 23– 28]. Notably, their structure can satisfy aforementioned requirements, reducing Eu 3+ ions to Eu 2+ ions and making Eu 2+ ions stable. They are also widely used as excellent host materials for luminescent material applications because of the high chemical stability [ 29, 30] and so on. Among various zeolites, zeolite-3A (
